<MAN>
  <LANGUAGE>eng</LANGUAGE>
  <TITLE>fprintfMat  </TITLE>
  <TYPE>Scilab Function  </TYPE>
  <DATE>Aug 1999  </DATE>
  <SHORT_DESCRIPTION name="fprintfMat"> print a matrix in a file.  </SHORT_DESCRIPTION>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>fprintfMat(fil,M [,format,text])  </CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>
  </CALLING_SEQUENCE>
  <PARAM>
 <PARAM_INDENT>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>fil</PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
    : a string, the pathname of the file to be scanned. 
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>M  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
    : A matrix of real numbers.
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>format  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
    : a character string, a C like format. This is an optional
    parameter, the default value is <VERB>"%f"</VERB>
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>text</PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
    : a string matrix giving non numerical comments stored 
   at the beginning of the file.
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
 </PARAM_INDENT>
  </PARAM>
  <DESCRIPTION>
  <P>
  </P>
  <P>
    The <VERB>fprintfMat</VERB> function prints a matrix in a formated file. Each row
    of the matrix give a line in the file. If <VERB>text</VERB> is
    given then the elements of <VERB>text</VERB> are inserted
    columnwise at the beginning of the file one element per line. 
  </P>
  </DESCRIPTION>
  <EXAMPLE><![CDATA[
n=50;
a=rand(n,n,'u');
fprintfMat(TMPDIR+'/Mat',a,'%5.2f');
a1=fscanfMat(TMPDIR+'/Mat');
 ]]></EXAMPLE>
